Answers to questions:
1. The design I picked for part 1.7 is sending an instance of brickerGameManager to hte constructor of the
strategy.
The advantages of using this approach is that it helps encapsulation by leaving the responsibility of
adding and removing game objects to brickerGameManager only. This could prevent bugs in the code.
On the other hand, The rest of the API of brickerGameManager can be seen by the brick strategy, and some of it
isn't needed by the strategy.

2. The way I implemented the display of the player's lives in the game is by creating two classes: one ofr the
 numerical life renderer and one for the graphical life renderer.
 In the brickerGameManager class I kept a Counter object of the current number of lives in the game and a
 function that returns the counter's value and the function is used by the twolife rendering classes.
 The numerical life renderer is in charge of displaying the current number of lives in the game in text.
 The graphical life renderer is incharge of displaying the current number of lives in the game graphically.

 3. The Brick strategies are all implementing a collision strategy interface, meaning that on collision each
 one of them applies a different strategy behaviour. In brickerGameManager class there is a Counter object for
 the current number of bricks in the game that is sent to the brick strategies together with an instance of
 brickerGameManager.
 BasicCollisionStrategy - on collision of brick with another game object, removes the brick using the
 brickerGameManager and decrements the current number of bricks in the game by one.
 MoreBallsStrategy - on collision of brick with another game object, creates two pucks(using the original ball
 and it's attributes needed for creating a puck, that are passed to the constructor of the strategy). The
 pucks are created with the constructor of Ball.
 Then, the brick is removed and the current number of bricks in the game is decremented by one.
 AddPaddleStrategy - for this strategy I have created a class SecondaryPaddle for the secondary paddle, that
 the strategy will add to the game. This class uses composition. It has a game object that it is created
 according to and moves according to.
 The strategy checks with brickerGameManager instance if there isn't a secondary paddle in the game
 currently, and if so, it creates a secondary paddle(with mai paddle sent to it's constructor). Then, it
 removes the brick from the game and decrements the number of current bricks by one similarly to
 basicCollisionStrategy.
 ChangeCameraStrategy - the object to follow(in this case the main ball) is sent to the constructor of the
 strategy. The brickerGameManager instance checks that there isn't a change of camera activated already and
 the tag of the ball is checked to see that the main ball is the one that collided with the brick. If so, then
 we set the camera to follow the main ball. We remove the brick and decrement the number of bricks by
 one.
 AddLifeStrategy - For this strategy, I added a class called fallingLife for the lives that we need to fall
 down from the brick. The class increases the number of lives once it collides with the main paddle of the
 game.
 The AddLifeStrategy gets in the constructor a Counter object of the current number of lives in the game.
 On collision of brick with another game object, it creates a FallingLife game object using the constant heart
 image path and width of the life rendered in the graphical renderer.
 it adds the falling life to the game and sets it's position and velocity. Then, the brick is removed and the
 current number of lives in the game is decremented by 1.

4. For the behaviour of double strategy, I implemented a double strategy class that has an array of collision
  strategies that are sent to it's constructor. On collision with the brick, we go over the array and activate
  the strategy onCollision function.
  Limiting the double strategy to have no more than 3 special strategies was done in the BrickStrategyFactory
  class. if a special strategy needs to be picked, the buildStrategy function creates a Counter object
  containing the number of double strategies for the brick. Then we have a private functions for picking a
  special brick strategy. If the special strategy that is picked is a double strategy, we check first that the
   number of double strategies isn't 2. if so, we increment the counter by one and create a double strategy
   that again picks two special strategies. If another double strategy is picked, then the counter is again
   incremented by one and the next time we pick a special strategy, it will go into the if condition, and
   will pick between 4 options of special strategies(that don't include the option of double strategy) which
   is done by generating a random integer between 0 to 40 instead of 0 to 50.
